mindmap
  root((Type-2 Diabetes Reversal Research))
    Definitions & terminology
      Remission: HbA1c <6.5% (or <6.0%) without diabetes meds for ≥3 months
      Reversal often used interchangeably; not a permanent cure
      ADA / Diabetes UK consensus frameworks guide clinical use
    Biological mechanisms
      Twin Cycle: excess fat → liver insulin resistance → hyperinsulinemia → pancreatic fat
      Pancreatic fat impairs beta-cell insulin secretion
      Weight loss reduces liver & pancreatic fat → restores beta-cell function
      Beta-cell dedifferentiation may be partially reversible
      Visceral fat drives systemic insulin resistance & inflammation
    Evidence-based interventions
      Low-calorie / formula diets (DiRECT: ~46% remission at 1 yr)
      Sustained weight loss: ~10–15 kg often needed
      Low-carbohydrate / Mediterranean dietary patterns
      Metabolic (bariatric) surgery: 50–80% remission in trials
      Structured lifestyle: diet + physical activity + behavioral support
      GLP-1 agonists: strong glycemic control; remission data emerging
    Landmark research
      DiRECT trial (UK): primary-care weight management
      Look AHEAD: major weight loss benefits; limited formal remission
      Counterpoint: very-low-calorie diet proof-of-concept
      2025 meta-analyses confirm multicomponent interventions work
      Bariatric surgery RCTs vs medical care: RR ~8 for remission at 1 yr
    Predictors of success
      Shorter diabetes duration (<6 years better)
      Higher baseline beta-cell reserve
      Greater & sustained weight loss
      Lower starting HbA1c & medication burden
      Not all responders: lean T2D & long-standing disease harder
    Limitations & open questions
      Relapse common if weight regained
      Long-term durability beyond 5 years still studied
      Access, cost, and behavioral sustainability
      Individual variation; no one-size-fits-all protocol
      Distinction from prevention of progression in prediabetes
